<br>
I like low populations; knowing everyone makes for a great comunity feel on a sever.  I like that I keep meeting real bona-fide EQ newbies here.  I like that &quot;uber twink&quot; here means &quot;full banded&quot;.  I like running into people that ask &quot;where are you from?&quot; and they mean &quot;what was your character's starting city?&quot;, not &quot;what city do you live in out there in RL?&quot;<br>
<br>
I fully intend to play up to 60 on FV and have fun killing off &quot;uber&quot; mobs.  Play of the game itself is fun and I've got enough munchkin in me to like optimizing my character (items, xp gain, etc.).  That's powergaming, but it has absolutely nothing to do with whether or not I also RP; they're completely orthogonal.  That RP-char I had, for instance, was a warrior -- 51 in 17 days all by grouping with other skilled players, no xp-twinking.  Being a skilled player has nothing to do with whether you RP or not.<br>
<br>
Actually, IMHO, being a skilled player is the top criteria on whether or not you are fun to have around.  RP is lots of fun, but it's icing, not cake.  You have to be a truly amazing personality for people to like you even when you keep getting them killed.  BTW, I knew a guy like that.  He was so much fun to have around you (almost) didn't mind the xp loss.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=valquisssilverpalm>Valquiss Silverpalm</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 90<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(12/27/01 11:30:11 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=173.topic&index=20>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_lightbulb.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: I'm here ..</span><hr size=1> Hail<br>
<br>
As a random aside, I would like to indicate a certain viewpoint I have when it comes to RP and fighting in our fantasy setting of Norrath.<br>
<br>
We are all adventures, soldiers, mercenaries, or what have you.  For one reason or another, we all portray characters who go out and kill things, putting our own lives on the line to do it.  That's serious stuff and often does not allow time for long expository speaches!  Simply because people step into shorthand and stop talking about their long lost cousin who holds the answer to some mystery in their past does not mean people aren't role-playing anymore, if they happen to be at a dangerous camp or in the middle of a dungeon.  It's only bloody natural, in RL or otherwise.<br>
<br>
I am not a major fan of game appreviations, and I've never said &quot;woot&quot; and likely never will in my entire career as my current character.  But shorthand is reasonable in a battle, even annoying stuff like &quot;woot&quot; and, if appropriate to a character's vocab, &quot;wtf.&quot;  Well, it can't really be pronounced, but other than that.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   In fact, people who are fighting often could easily find battlefield slang slipping into more relaxed conversation.  My example to prove this is Vietnam.  More bloody shorthand was invented by soldiers in that environment....  Partially convenience, I think, partially long exposure to strange situations for which they didn't have words for before, and partially out of a desire to distinguish Us from Them on any basis available.  I don't know, I'm not an expert.<br>
<br>
Point is, catch me in a city and I'll be happy to role-play in detail, assuming I have the time.  Catch me fighting in a group and my RP is reduced to a few key emotes, some catch phrases, and a general attitude.  Why?  Because it's natural.  And anyone who wants to tell me I'm not a role-player can line up right now and throw the first stone.<br>
<br>
Valquiss Silverpalm<br>
<br>
